Explanation — how I derived the parameters

- The route handled by PUT /admin/posts/{post} is implemented by Admin\PostController::update(PostsRequest $request, Post $post).
- The request validation rules are defined in app/Http/Requests/Admin/PostsRequest.php. Those rules declare required and optional fields:
  - title: required
  - content: required
  - posted_at: required, date
  - author_id: required, exists:users,id (an integer id)
  - thumbnail_id: nullable, exists:media,id (an integer id, optional)
  - slug: validated (prepared automatically from title) but the controller only persists the fields listed below.
- The controller uses $request->only(['title', 'content', 'posted_at', 'author_id', 'thumbnail_id']) when updating the model, so those are the fields the client may provide in the request body.
- The route model binding parameter {post} corresponds to the Post model. Post::getRouteKeyName() returns 'slug' for non-JSON (web) requests and 'id' if request()->expectsJson() — so the path parameter is typically a string slug for web requests (but can be an integer id for JSON API calls). For the Swagger parameter I document the path parameter as a required string (slug), noting it can also be an id when expecting JSON.
- Following Swagger 2.0 Parameter Object structure, there must be a path parameter for {post}, and a single body parameter describing the JSON object to send in the PUT request. The body schema lists properties, types/formats, and required fields matching PostsRequest rules.

